		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">An aperiodic system may still be ordered, like a quasicrystal, or it may arise as a periodic system to which disorder is added. The Quantum Hall Effect is an example where disorder effects play a crucial role. In both cases non-commutative geometry can be used to describe aspects of such systems. In many cases the non-commutative topological invariants could be successfully computed, yet the physical significance of only some of these invariants is understood. We propose to relate all these invariants to physical quantities and to develop the non-commutative geometry of solids further, specifically to describe the Quantum Hall effect in the edge channel picture also in the presence of dynamical localization, and ultimately with the goal to treat systems with many body interactions which are, for instance, necessary to understand the fractional Quantum Hall Effect.</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
